		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">One of the most successful applications of probability theory over the last two decades has been to problems in finance. The fundamental problem in mathematical finance is the pricing of derivatives. In a perfect frictionless market probability theory tells us how to derive unique fair prices for options from a stochastic model for the underlying.This proposal is concerned with finding the prices of exotic options within the Black-Scholes framework and with determining the effect of deviattions from the Black-Scholes model. Finding a way of dealing with market imperfections, such as transaction costs, discrete hedging and model mis-specification is critical for finding flexible approaches to the valuation of options.Stochastic calculus and diffusion theory provide a natural language for formulating problems in finance. The aim of this proposal will be to use this language and ideas from probability theory and elsewhere to characterise problems in derivative pricing and to find novel solutions.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
